          "body": "The chapter pivots at verse 7 with an affirmation so simple it is easy to pass over: 'The light is pleasant, and it is good for the eyes to see the sun.' In a book that has diagnosed vanity under the sun, this is a recalibration — the sun itself is good, the visible world is pleasant, existence is a gift. But verse 8 immediately installs the shadow: rejoice in all your years, yes — and remember the days of darkness, for they will be many. Everything to come is *hevel*. Two commentators mark the complexity here. Tremper Longman (*The Book of Ecclesiastes*, NICOT) reads the darkness as death's shadow, pressing joy toward urgency. Michael Fox (*A Time to Tear Down*) reads it as old age and suffering. Both readings reach the same pastoral conclusion: joy is not naive, and it is not optional. It is commanded precisely because darkness is real and many. The 'rejoice' of 11:8 is the same imperative that appears in the carpe diem passages of 2:24, 3:13, and 9:7-10 — Qohelet's consistent answer to vanity is not resignation but commanded, present enjoyment."
