          "body": "Ecclesiastes 11 does not stand alone — it is the practical threshold before the book's final word in chapter 12. The two chapters together form a closing diptych: chapter 11 commands action and joy while you have strength; chapter 12 commands remembering the Creator before the evil days come. The movement is from outward action (cast, sow, rejoice) to inward orientation (remember God). Both imperatives are grounded in the same theological reality named in 11:5 and 11:9: God makes all things, and God brings all things to judgment. The fear of God that chapter 12 will name as the conclusion of the whole matter (12:13-14) is not absent from chapter 11 — it is present in the shadow of judgment (11:9) and in the acknowledgment of divine inscrutable activity (11:5). Chapter 11 is where the book stops diagnosing and starts prescribing. Its prescriptions are not pious platitudes; they are hard-edged wisdom commands for finite creatures who do not know what is coming and will not get their season back."
