        "title": "Act broadly because outcomes belong to God — the wisdom of the cast bread",
        "range": "11:1-2",
        "excerpt": "Cast your bread on the surface of the waters, for you will find it after many days. Divide your portion to seven, or even to eight, for you do not know what misfortune may occur on the earth.",
        "body": "The opening imperative is not a proverb about charity, though interpreters from medieval Jewish commentators to Luther have read it as such. In context, 'bread on the waters' (*lechem al-pene hamayim*) most naturally evokes the ancient grain trade — merchant vessels carrying cargo across water, with return delayed by the rhythms of wind and market. Qohelet's argument is commercial: generous, risk-accepting action will find its return, though the timing is deferred ('after many days'). The deferral is not a discouragement; it is the structure of all productive action under creaturely uncertainty.\n\nVerse 2 extends the principle from single-venture courage to systematic diversification. 'Divide your portion to seven, or even to eight' is the wisdom of portfolio thinking: since catastrophe cannot be predicted, concentrate nowhere. The numbers seven and eight function as a Semitic idiom for 'the fullest possible distribution' (compare Proverbs 6:16; Amos 1:3 — 'for three transgressions and for four'). The ground is made explicit: 'you do not know what misfortune may occur.' The Hebrew *ra* (misfortune, disaster) here echoes the book's broader vocabulary for the evil that can befall a wise man as readily as a fool (see 9:11-12). Not knowing the disaster is not a reason to freeze — it is the reason to spread the seed as widely as possible.\n\nTim Keller's observation about this passage is apt: wisdom in Ecclesiastes is never the elimination of risk but the proper calibration of it. The fool is both the reckless man who casts everything on one throw *and* the paralyzed man who casts nothing. Qohelet is commanding neither gambling nor hoarding — he is commanding the courageous generosity of the person who trusts that the God who governs outcomes will honor comprehensive, forward-leaning action.\n\nThe canonical resonance with Proverbs 3:27-28 ('do not withhold good from those to whom it is due, when it is in your power to do it') and Psalm 112:5 ('the gracious man lends, he will maintain his cause in judgment') suggests that Qohelet's commercial metaphor has moral texture as well. The bread cast on the waters may carry the double meaning of generous investment and generous giving — both of which require trusting the Giver of all good things with the return.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shalach lechem* (cast bread) — *shalach* is the ordinary word for sending or casting; the image is of release, not careful placement. *Al-pene hamayim* — 'on the face of the waters' echoes Genesis 1:2; the same phrase used at creation, where the Spirit moved over the formless deep. The subtle echo may be intentional: the one who casts in trust is acting in a world where God hovers over outcomes."
