        "body": "Verse 6 is the practical resolution of the epistemological dilemma established in verses 2-5. You do not know which sowing will succeed — morning or evening, early planting or late. Qohelet's answer is not to wait for better information. His answer is to sow both. The agricultural imagery is precise: in ancient Levantine farming, different crops or different fields might receive seed at different times of the growing season; the farmer who plants only when he is certain will plant nothing, because certainty is never available.\n\nThe imperative structure is significant: 'sow your seed in the morning AND do not be idle in the evening.' This is not two separate suggestions; it is a paired command bracketing the entire working day. The logic is the inverse of verse 4: the wind-watcher produces nothing by watching; the morning-and-evening sower covers the ground because he understands that his job is effort and God's job is outcome. Howard Hendricks' dictum is apposite here: the believer who waits to know everything before acting will never begin; the one who acts under acknowledged ignorance partners with the God whose activity, though hidden, 'makes all things.'\n\nThe closing phrase — 'or whether both of them alike will be good' — is the chapter's most optimistic note before the pivot to darkness and judgment in verses 7-10. The word *tov* (good) appears here after its use in 11:7 ('it is good for the eyes to see the sun'). The God who makes all things may, in His freedom, prosper both the morning and the evening sowing. This is not a guarantee — it is a possibility that comprehensive effort keeps open, while concentrated caution forecloses it.\n\nThe practical wisdom of verse 6 anticipates the apostle Paul's agricultural metaphor in 1 Corinthians 3:6-7: one sows, another waters, but God gives the increase. Qohelet and Paul are not in tension; they share the same theology of creaturely effort and divine outcome. The sower's responsibility is comprehensive sowing; the harvest is God's. What the chapter forbids is the self-protective withholding of seed that masquerades as prudence."
