        "range": "11:7-8",
        "excerpt": "The light is pleasant, and it is good for the eyes to see the sun. Indeed, if a man should live many years, let him rejoice in them all, and let him remember the days of darkness, for they will be many.",
        "body": "The chapter's pivot from action to joy is marked by the affirmation of verse 7. After six verses of agricultural and commercial metaphor, Qohelet pauses for a lyric observation: light is sweet (*matoq*), seeing the sun is good (*tov*). In a book that has catalogued the vanity of all things 'under the sun,' this is a deliberate recovery of the goodness of the sun itself. Creation is not the problem; autonomous mastery of creation is. The visible world, with its light and warmth, is a gift — and acknowledging it as gift is the beginning of proper joy.\n\nVerse 8 extends the joy-command across the full span of a long life with a crucial double imperative. First: rejoice in all your years. The Hebrew *bekulam yismach* — 'in all of them let him rejoice' — refuses to parcel joy to good seasons only. Every year, including the difficult ones, is to be inhabited with joy. This aligns with the book's carpe diem passages (2:24; 3:12-13; 5:18-19; 9:7-9), each of which commands the same present-tense enjoyment of what God has given. Second — and this is the chapter's most sober note before the young man's address — remember the days of darkness, for they will be many.\n\nTwo interpretive trajectories divide orthodox commentators here. Tremper Longman (NICOT) reads 'days of darkness' as death itself — the darkness of the grave that Qohelet has invoked throughout the book (see 6:4-5, where the stillborn child 'comes in futility and goes into obscurity and its name is covered in darkness'). Michael Fox reads it as the accumulated suffering and deterioration of old age, developed in detail in chapter 12's famous allegory. The pastoral force is the same on either reading: joy must be exercised *with the shadow in view*, not in ignorance of it. This is what makes Ecclesiastes' joy so different from mere optimism — it is commanded in full knowledge that darkness is real, many, and coming.\n\nThe chapter closes verse 8 with the book's thesis word: *hevel* — 'everything that is to come will be futility.' This is not nihilism appended to a joy command; it is the theological frame that gives the joy command its urgency. Because the future is vapor, the present is not optional. Rejoice now, in all your years, because you cannot bank joy for later.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Matoq* (sweet, pleasant, v.7) — used elsewhere of honey (Judges 14:18; Proverbs 16:24), the sweetest thing the ancient palate knew. To call light sweet is to register it at the highest register of creaturely delight. *Hevel* (futility, v.8) — the book's thesis word, here applied to 'everything that is to come' (*kol sheyavo*), which most naturally refers to the future in general, not to any specific event."
